    <h2 class="date-header">November 24, 2009</h2>

	<div class="entry-author-chris_baggott entry-type-post entry" id="entry-6a00d8345175d669e2012875d0c248970c">
       <div class="entry-inner">
					<h3 class="entry-header"><a href="https://exacttarget.typepad.com/chrisbaggott/2009/11/im-doing-some-blogging-on-the-job-market.html">I'm doing some blogging on the job market</a></h3>
		



		<div class="entry-content">

			<div class="entry-body">
				<p>I&#39;ve been invited to guest blog for CareerBuilder as part of their SEO blogging efforts around the Resume Service.&#0160; <a href="http://resumeblog.careerbuilder.com/blog/resume-writing-advice-2" title="Online Resume">http://resumeblog.careerbuilder.com/blog/resume-writing-advice-2</a></p><p></p><p>I support CB&#39;s effort because as someone who sees a lot of
resumes, I know how difficult it is to differentiate yourself.&#0160;&#0160; I&#39;m
dismayed to say how many perhaps great candidates never make it close
to a conversation because they look just like everyone else.&#0160;&#0160; Let&#39;s
face it, in many ways it&#39;s a cruel and faceless process.&#0160;&#0160; <br /><br />So
it&#39;s kind of fun to be able to endorse a service I really believe in,
and perhaps help some deserving people become aware of an alternative
to the resume template in their word processor software. </p>
